C# Code for Large Constraints
The constraints in your image are quite high (n up to 3 \times 10^5 and assetAmounts up to 2 \times 10^9). This confirms two things for the code:
 * Performance: We must use the O(n) prefix sum approach (the nested loop approach would be O(n^2) and would time out).
 * Data Types: The sums will exceed the capacity of a standard int. We must use long (64-bit integer) to calculate the totals.
using System;

public class Solution
{
    public static long getMinimumTransactions(int[] assetAmounts)
    {
        int n = assetAmounts.Length;
        long totalSum = 0;

        // Calculate total sum using long to prevent overflow
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        {
            totalSum += assetAmounts[i];
        }

        long currentA = 0;
        long minTransactions = long.MaxValue;

        // Check every possible split point j (from 1 to n-1)
        // In the loop, i represents the index, so i=0 is split j=1
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 1; i++)
        {
            currentA += assetAmounts[i];
            long currentB = totalSum - currentA;

            long diff = Math.Abs(currentA - currentB);

            if (diff < minTransactions)
            {
                minTransactions = diff;
            }
        }

        return minTransactions;
    }
}

Why this is optimal
 * Time: By pre-calculating the totalSum, we turn a complex "re-summing" problem into a simple subtraction problem inside a single loop.
 * Space: We don't create any new arrays or lists, keeping the memory footprint minimal.
